Commit Message:
initial submission

Should produce single/multi units, differentiable by spike waveforms and
location on electrode. Does NOT further refine the sort for single
units.

mexing on Linux

mex_CUDA_glnxa64.xml is a settings file that works on Linux, as long as
it knows where the CUDA paths are. These paths can be added to the
system path by following instructions from readme.txt.
significant changes, relating to optimization strategies mostly

some added tricks and computing projections of templates

ops.nNeig is the number of most similar templates to compute projections
of.
rez.iNeigh is the resulting indices of these "neighboring" templates.
rez.cProj is the nNeigh by nSpikes matrix of projections.

Allow optimizePeaks to operate on smaller recordings

If the number of spikes was less than nSpikesPerBatch (4000) and initialization
is 'fromData', then kilosort would crash, because optimizePeaks would do
nothing.
Fix bug in new indexing of spikes in optimizepeaks

Store .npy files in a new directory each time

Feels more convenient for the user to be able to compare both versions.

Change data in 'spike_clusters.npy' to int32 instead of uint32

This commit brings the behavior of `rezToPhy.m` in-line with the documentation.
The documentation and phy's template gui both expect int32 cluster ids, but
before this commit rezToPhy wrote cluster ids as uint32.
